To start a new process in C++ with one file descriptor connected to its input and output, you can use the `fork()` and `dup2()` functions. Here's a simple example:

```cpp
#include <unistd.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>

int main() {
    int fd[2];
    pipe(fd);  // Create a pipe

    pid_t pid = fork();  // Fork a new process

    if (pid == -1) {
        perror("fork");
        return 1;
    } else if (pid == 0) {  // Child process
        close(fd[1]);  // Close the write end in the child
        dup2(fd[0], 0);  // Duplicate the read end to stdin
        dup2(fd[0], 1);  // Duplicate the read end to stdout
        close(fd[0]);  // Close the read end
        execlp("/bin/cat", "cat", NULL);  // Execute a command
        perror("execlp");
        _exit(1);
    } else {  // Parent process
        close(fd[0]);  // Close the read end in the parent
        // You can write to fd[1] and read from fd[1] in the parent process
        printf("Parent process: Writing to child\n");
        write(fd[1], "Hello from parent!", 17);
        close(fd[1]);  // Close the write end in the parent
        wait(NULL);  // Wait for the child to finish
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This code creates a pipe and forges a child process. In the child, the read end of the pipe is duplicated to both standard input and standard output, effectively redirecting the child's IO to the pipe. The parent process can then write to the write end of the pipe and read from the write end of the pipe (though typically, the parent would write and the child would read).
